Supplementary Material

Author: Michael S. Feurstein

Goal is to validate the sbl-experiment analysis procedure, based on the NCSS documentation, which is using a sample dataset from Chow and Liu (1999). The dataset is taken from the NCSS documentation page 234-6. It is an Analysis of 2x2 Cross-Over Design using T-Tests and ANOVA.

Dataset

The original dataset is taken from the NCSS documentation. See Figure 1 below.

Figure 1: ChowLiu73 Dataset (Screenshot from NCSS documentation)

df <- read.csv("dataset.csv", sep = ";", dec = ",", header = TRUE)

Dataframe

We added subject and treatment column and flattened the dataset.

df

Summary of data

Calculate mean and standard deviation.

df %>%
  group_by(treatment) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(response), sd = sd(response))

Normality tests

Visual tests

Note that we have used a named mapping which resembled the original experiment. Natural language treatment is actually treatment R in NCSS documentation. Key-Value treatment is actually treatment T in NCSS documentation.

# histogram on duration
hist(df$response[df$treatment == "nl"], main = "Natural Language (Treatment R)", xlab = "Response")
hist(df$response[df$treatment == "kv"], main = "Key-Value (Treatment T)", xlab = "Response")

Statistical tests

Note that in the NCSS documentation four different normality tests are presented for period differences per sequence. We only test Shapiro-Wilk and Skewness by DAgostino. First the period differences need to be calculated and stored in a new data.frame called p1.

p1 <- df %>%
  group_by(subject, sequence) %>%
  summarize(difference = response[1]-response[2])
p1

p1 %>%
  group_by(sequence) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(difference))

Tests of the Normality Assumption for the Period Differences in Sequence 1

shapiro.test(p1$difference[p1$sequence == "1"])
agostino.test(p1$difference[p1$sequence == "1"], alternative = "two.sided")

Tests of the Normality Assumption for the Subject Totals in Sequence 1

shapiro.test(p2$total[p2$sequence == "1"])
agostino.test(p2$total[p2$sequence == "1"], alternative = "two.sided")

Tests of the Normality Assumption for the Period Differences in Sequence 2

shapiro.test(p1$difference[p1$sequence == "2"])
agostino.test(p1$difference[p1$sequence == "2"], alternative = "two.sided")

Validation: the values from the above normality tests are the exact same as in the NCSS documentation.

See the following screenshot from NCSS documentation in Figure 2 to compare values for validation check. Shapiro-Wilk and DAgostino Skewness test p-values can be replicated.

Figure 2: Tests for Normality in NCSS documentation (Screenshot from NCSS documentation)

Cross-over analysis

Before we can do T-Tests or an ANOVA we need check for carryover effects.

Test for Period and Carryover effects

Note that we were not able replicate the exact numbers. However we also failed to reject the assumption of equal period effects at the 0.05 significance level and failed to reject the assumption of equal carryover effects at the 0.05 significance level.

p2 <- df %>%
  group_by(subject, sequence) %>%
  summarize(total = response[1]+response[2])
p2

Period Effect

Results are nearly the same.

## two-sided, paired t-test --> period effect
t.test(response ~ period , data = df, paired = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95, alternative = "two.sided")

Carryover Effect

Results are not the same as in NCSS doc.

## two-sided, paired t-test --> carryover effect
t.test(response ~ sequence, data = df, paired = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95, alternative = "two.sided")

using totals

## two-sided, paired t-test --> carryover effect
t.test(total ~ sequence, data = p2, paired = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95, alternative = "two.sided")

Validation: we could not exactly replicate the numbers, however also failed to reject assumption for null hypotheses of period and carryover effects.

Figure 3: Period and Carryover Effects from NCSS Documentation (Screenshot from NCSS documentation)

T-Test for Treatment Effect

We cannot exactly replicate the values with separate T-Tests but get very close, however with a linear mixed model as shown below we can exactly replicate the results from the NCSS documentation. In both cases (t-tests and linear mixed model) the two treatment means in a 2x2 cross-over study are not significantly different as also documented in the NCSS documentation.

## two-sided, paired t-test
t.test(x = df$response[df$treatment == "nl"], y = df$response[df$treatment == "kv"], paired = TRUE, conf.level = 0.95, alternative = "two.sided")

Analysis of Variance (linear mixed model) using lmer

Based on input from Thomas Rusch (WU Vienna Competence Center for Empirical Research Methods) using a linear mixed model and a slideset (Lukas Meier: Multiple Treatments on the Same Experimental Unit) which references Jones and Kenward (2014) explaining how to model a carryover effect as a sequence effect or as an interaction effect.

Linear mixed model including carryover effect as a sequence effect

###### Part 1: Linear Regression (Linear Mixed Model) ####
# based on input from Thomas Rusch + slideset from Meier
# model as a sequence effect
m_seq<-lmer(response~treatment+period+sequence+(1|subject),data=df)
# Madeyski and Kitchenham actually argue to leave out sequence
#m_seq<-lmer(response~period+treatment+(1|subject),data=df)
#anova(m_seq)
summary(m_seq)
#fixef(m_seq)

## extract coefficients
#coefs_seq <- data.frame(coef(summary(m_seq)))
#coefs_seq$df.Satt <- coef(summary(m_seq))[, 3]
## get approximate p-values
#coefs_seq$p.Satt <- coef(summary(m_seq))[, 5]
#coefs_seq
coefs_final <- coefs_seq
coefs_final %>% filter(rownames(coefs_final) %in% c('treatmentnl'))
coefs_final
anova(m_seq)
F_to_eta2(0.3754, df = 1, df_error = 22)

Linear mixed model including carryover effect as an interaction effect

###### Part 2: Linear Regression (Linear Mixed Model) ####
# based on input from Thomas Rusch + slideset from Meier
# model as an interaction effect
m_int<-lmer(response~treatment*period+(1|subject),data=df)
#anova(m_int)
summary(m_int)
fixef(m_int)

# extract coefficients
coefs_int <- data.frame(coef(summary(m_int)))
coefs_int$df.Satt <- coef(summary(m_int))[, 3]
# get approximate p-values
coefs_int$p.Satt <- coef(summary(m_int))[, 5]
coefs_int
anova(m_int, m_seq)

Multiple Comparisons of Means: Tukey Contrasts

summary(glht(m_seq, linfct=mcp(treatment="Tukey")))

confint(m_seq)

We replicated period and carryover effects and also the treatment effect. All from the linear mixed models. The above would still need some code refinements and cleanups (TODO).

Where to read the correct values:

  • Period effect is used from model based on sequence effect (m_seq)

  • Carryover effect is used from model based on interaction effect (m_int)

  • Treatment effect can be used from both models (same result)

Analysis of Variance (one-way ANOVA) using aov

Based on input from Stefan Sobernig

# lmer formula: response~treatment+period+sequence+(1|subject)
# source: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/71914/what-does-the-anova-command-do-with-a-lmer-model-object?newreg=9a9a41dc9b154ae09f9aec1620081ba6
model <- aov(response~treatment+period+sequence+Error(subject/treatment), data=df)
summary(model)

Tukey HSD

TukeyHSD(model, "treatment", conf.level=.95, ordered = TRUE)

Validation: the one-way ANOVA with lmer can replicate the results from the NCSS documentation. See Figure 4 for validation check.

Figure 4: T-Test for Treatment Effect from NCSS Documentation(Screenshot from NCSS documentation)

Plot of Sequence-by-Period Means

Note that this plot can be replicated.

np <- df %>%
  group_by(treatment, period) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(response))

pd = position_dodge(0)
np.plot <- ggplot(np, aes(x = period,
               y = mean,
               color = treatment,
               group = treatment)) +
  geom_point(shape  = 15,
             size   = 4,
             position = pd) +
  geom_line() + theme(
    legend.position = c(.99, .99),
    legend.justification = c("right", "top"),
    legend.box.just = "right",
    legend.margin = margin(4, 4, 4, 4),
    axis.title   = element_text(face = "bold"),
    axis.text    = element_text(face = "bold"),
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0)
  ) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0.5, 2.5),breaks=seq(1,2),minor_breaks=NULL) +
  ylab("Mean Response") +
  xlab("Period") +
  labs(color = "Treatment")

np.plot

Effect Size

# R-squared
performance::r2(m_seq)

# F2 calculations
# Source: https://joshuawiley.com/MonashHonoursStatistics/LMM_Comparison.html

# Calculate conditional F2
F2c <- (0.636^2)/(1-0.636^2)
F2c

# Calculate marginal F2
F2m <- (0.017^2)/(1-0.017^2)
F2m

# Backup
# Partial eta-square
anova(m_seq)
F_to_eta2(0.3754, df = 1, df_error = 22)

# Beta coefficient
effectsize(m_int)
#effectsize::standardize_parameters(model_seq, method = "pseudo")
#effectsize::standardize_parameters(model_seq, method = "refit")

Tukey HSD

N <- 48 # sample size
k <- 2 # number of treatments
n <- N / k # number of samples per group

# Mean Square
plants <- split(df, df$treatment)

sse <- sum(Reduce('+', lapply(plants, function(x) {
  (length(x[,1]) - 1) * sd(x[,1])^2
})))

mse <- sse / (N - k)
mse
confint(m_seq)

# q-value
q.value <- qtukey(p = 0.95, nmeans = k, df = N - k)
q.value

tukey.hsd <- q.value * sqrt(mse/n)
tukey.hsd

means <- tapply(df$response, df$sequence, mean)
trt1.ctrl.diff <- means[2] - means[1]
trt1.ctrl.diff

trt1.ctrl.diff.upper <- trt1.ctrl.diff + q.value * sqrt(mse / 2 * (2 / n))
trt1.ctrl.diff.lower <- trt1.ctrl.diff - q.value * sqrt(mse / 2 * (2 / n))
trt1.ctrl.diff.lower
trt1.ctrl.diff.upper
